1
00:01:08,568 --> 00:01:12,279
Iceland is a stable democracy with a high standard of living -

2
00:01:12,447 --> 00:01:13,906
- and, until recently -

3
00:01:14,074 --> 00:01:17,284
- extremely low unemployment and government debt.

4
00:01:19,370 --> 00:01:23,040
We had the complete infrastructure of a modern society.

5
00:01:23,416 --> 00:01:25,918
Clean energy, food production.

6
00:01:26,086 --> 00:01:28,504
Fisheries with a quota system to manage them.

7
00:01:28,671 --> 00:01:30,756
Good healthcare, education, clean air.

8
00:01:33,676 --> 00:01:34,843
Not much crime.

9
00:01:35,011 --> 00:01:37,346
It's a good place for families to live.

10
00:01:37,514 --> 00:01:39,389
We had almost end-of-history status.

11
00:01:42,060 --> 00:01:46,855
But in 2000, Iceland's government began a broad policy of deregulation -

12
00:01:47,023 --> 00:01:49,691
- that would have disastrous consequences -

13
00:01:49,859 --> 00:01:53,862
- first for the environment and then for the economy.

14
00:01:54,030 --> 00:01:57,825
They started by allowing multinational corporations like Alcoa -

15
00:01:57,992 --> 00:02:00,369
- to build giant aluminum-smelting plants -

16
00:02:00,537 --> 00:02:05,374
- and exploit lceland's geothermal and hydroelectric energy sources.

17
00:02:05,875 --> 00:02:08,752
Many of the most beautiful areas in the highlands -

18
00:02:08,920 --> 00:02:13,465
- with the most spectacular colors are geothermal.

19
00:02:14,217 --> 00:02:16,260
So nothing comes without consequence.

20
00:02:54,924 --> 00:02:56,175
At the same time -

21
00:02:56,342 --> 00:03:00,012
- the government privatized Iceland's three largest banks.

22
00:03:00,180 --> 00:03:02,681
The result was one of the purest experiments -

23
00:03:02,849 --> 00:03:05,809
- in financial deregulation ever conducted.

24
00:03:11,149 --> 00:03:14,484
We have had enough. How could all of this happen?

25
00:03:15,695 --> 00:03:20,449
Finance took over and more or less wrecked the place.

26
00:03:21,367 --> 00:03:24,161
In a five-year period, these three tiny banks -

27
00:03:24,329 --> 00:03:26,788
- which had never operated outside of lceland -

28
00:03:26,956 --> 00:03:29,875
- borrowed 1 20 billion dollars -

29
00:03:30,043 --> 00:03:33,128
- 1 0 times the size of Iceland's economy.

30
00:03:33,296 --> 00:03:35,547
The bankers showered money on themselves -

31
00:03:35,715 --> 00:03:37,633
- each other, and their friends.

32
00:03:37,800 --> 00:03:39,468
There was a massive bubble.

33
00:03:39,636 --> 00:03:42,971
Stock prices went up by a factor of nine.

34
00:03:43,139 --> 00:03:45,349
House prices more than doubled.

35
00:03:47,435 --> 00:03:51,688
Iceland's bubble gave rise to people like Jon Asgeir Johannesson.

36
00:03:51,856 --> 00:03:56,652
He borrowed billions to buy up high-end retail businesses in London.

37
00:03:56,819 --> 00:03:59,029
He also bought a pinstriped private jet -

38
00:03:59,197 --> 00:04:00,989
- a 40-million-dollar yacht -

39
00:04:01,157 --> 00:04:03,242
- and a Manhattan penthouse.

40
00:04:03,409 --> 00:04:05,244
Newspapers always had the headline:

41
00:04:05,411 --> 00:04:08,455
This millionaire bought this company -

42
00:04:08,623 --> 00:04:13,794
- in the U.K. or in Finland or in France or wherever -

43
00:04:13,962 --> 00:04:15,254
- instead of saying:

44
00:04:15,421 --> 00:04:19,174
"This millionaire took a billion-dollar loan -

45
00:04:19,342 --> 00:04:23,679
- to buy this company, and he took it from your local bank."

46
00:04:23,846 --> 00:04:25,847
The banks set up money market funds -

47
00:04:26,015 --> 00:04:29,184
- and the banks advised deposit-holders to withdraw money -

48
00:04:29,352 --> 00:04:31,603
- and put them in the money market funds.

49
00:04:31,771 --> 00:04:34,189
The Ponzi scheme needed everything it could.

50
00:04:34,357 --> 00:04:37,484
American accounting firms like KPMG -

51
00:04:37,652 --> 00:04:40,112
- audited the Icelandic banks and investment firms -

52
00:04:40,280 --> 00:04:42,072
- and found nothing wrong.

53
00:04:42,240 --> 00:04:45,867
And American credit-rating agencies said lceland was wonderful.

54
00:04:46,035 --> 00:04:47,160
In February 2007 -

55
00:04:50,873 --> 00:04:54,710
- the rating agency upgraded the banks to the highest possible rate, triple-A.

56
00:04:54,877 --> 00:04:59,756
It went so far as the government here traveling with the bankers -

57
00:04:59,924 --> 00:05:02,801
- as a PR show.

58
00:05:05,013 --> 00:05:08,598
When Iceland's banks collapsed at the end of 2008 -

59
00:05:08,766 --> 00:05:12,060
- unemployment tripled in six months.

60
00:05:15,148 --> 00:05:18,567
There is nobody unaffected in Iceland.

61
00:05:24,240 --> 00:05:26,158
A lot of people lost their savings.

62
00:05:26,326 --> 00:05:28,410
Yes, that's the case.

63
00:05:28,578 --> 00:05:31,663
Government regulators who should've been protecting the citizens -

64
00:05:33,249 --> 00:05:34,416
- had done nothing.

65
00:05:35,418 --> 00:05:38,962
You have two lawyers from the regulator going down to a bank -

66
00:05:39,130 --> 00:05:41,048
- to talk about some issue.

67
00:05:41,215 --> 00:05:42,841
When they approach the bank -

68
00:05:43,009 --> 00:05:48,305
- they would see 1 9 SUVs outside the bank.

69
00:05:48,473 --> 00:05:49,639
You enter the bank -

70
00:05:49,807 --> 00:05:54,019
- and you have the 1 9 lawyers sitting in front of you, right -

71
00:05:54,187 --> 00:05:59,566
- very well prepared, ready to kill any argument you make.

72
00:05:59,734 --> 00:06:02,819
And then, if you do really well, they'll offer you a job.

73
00:06:03,279 --> 00:06:06,281
One-third of Iceland's financial regulators -

74
00:06:06,449 --> 00:06:08,867
- went to work for the banks.

75
00:06:10,119 --> 00:06:12,120
But this is a universal problem, huh?

76
00:06:12,288 --> 00:06:14,998
In New York, you have the same problem, right?

77
00:06:46,239 --> 00:06:49,032
What do you think of Wall Street incomes these days?

78
00:06:49,200 --> 00:06:50,700
Excessive.

79
00:06:52,995 --> 00:06:56,081
I've been told it's extremely difficult for the lMF -

80
00:06:56,249 --> 00:06:58,291
- to criticize the United States.

81
00:06:58,459 --> 00:06:59,584
I wouldn't say that.

82
00:07:06,384 --> 00:07:10,178
We deeply regret our breaches of U.S. law.

83
00:07:13,891 --> 00:07:17,853
They're amazed at how much cocaine these Wall Streeters can use -

84
00:07:18,020 --> 00:07:20,188
- and get up and go to work the next day.

85
00:07:23,067 --> 00:07:27,112
I didn't know what credit default swaps are.

86
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:28,905
I'm a little bit old-fashioned.

87
00:07:34,287 --> 00:07:36,746
Has Larry Summers ever expressed remorse?

88
00:07:36,914 --> 00:07:38,707
I don't hear confessions.

89
00:07:53,389 --> 00:07:55,307
The government's just writing checks.

90
00:07:55,475 --> 00:07:58,727
That's plan A, that's plan B and that's plan C.

91
00:07:58,895 --> 00:08:02,772
Would you support legal controls on executive pay?

92
00:08:03,441 --> 00:08:04,649
I would not.

93
00:08:08,279 --> 00:08:12,073
Are you comfortable with the level of compensation in financial services?

94
00:08:12,241 --> 00:08:13,742
If they've earned it, yes, I am.

95
00:08:13,910 --> 00:08:15,952
-Do you think they've earned it? -l think so.

96
00:08:19,415 --> 00:08:22,125
And so you've helped these people blow the world up?

97
00:08:22,293 --> 00:08:23,335
You could say that.

98
00:08:32,929 --> 00:08:36,598
They were having massive private gains at public loss.

99
00:08:45,233 --> 00:08:48,318
When you think you can create something out of nothing -

100
00:08:48,486 --> 00:08:49,945
- it's difficult to resist.

101
00:09:04,877 --> 00:09:08,004
I'm concerned people want to go back to the old way -

102
00:09:08,172 --> 00:09:10,840
- the way they were operating prior to the crisis.

103
00:09:21,644 --> 00:09:25,021
I was getting a lot of anonymous e-mails from bankers saying:

104
00:09:25,189 --> 00:09:27,983
"You can't quote me, but I'm really concerned."

105
00:09:33,990 --> 00:09:35,699
Why do you think there isn't -

106
00:09:35,866 --> 00:09:38,577
- a more systematic investigation being undertaken?

107
00:09:38,744 --> 00:09:40,704
Because then you'll find the culprits.

108
00:09:44,041 --> 00:09:48,628
You think Columbia Business School has any conflict-of-interest problem?

109
00:09:49,005 --> 00:09:50,171
I don't see that we do.

110
00:10:01,017 --> 00:10:02,642
The regulators didn't do their job.

111
00:10:02,810 --> 00:10:06,730
They had the power to do every case that I made. They just didn't want to.

112
00:10:24,957 --> 00:10:27,125
Lehman Brothers, one of the most venerable -

113
00:10:27,293 --> 00:10:30,670
- and biggest investment banks, was forced to declare itself bankrupt.

114
00:10:30,838 --> 00:10:33,923
Another, Merrill Lynch, was forced to sell itself today.

115
00:10:34,091 --> 00:10:38,261
World financial markets are way down, following dramatic developments - .

116
00:10:46,646 --> 00:10:47,812
In September 2008 -

117
00:10:47,980 --> 00:10:50,982
- the bankruptcy of the U.S. investment bank Lehman Brothers -

118
00:10:52,610 --> 00:10:56,196
- and the collapse of the world's largest insurance company, AIG -

119
00:10:56,364 --> 00:10:57,906
- triggered a global crisis.

120
00:10:58,074 --> 00:11:00,241
Fears gripped markets overnight - .

121
00:11:00,409 --> 00:11:01,910
Stocks fell off a cliff.

122
00:11:02,078 --> 00:11:04,913
The largest single point drop in history.

123
00:11:05,081 --> 00:11:07,082
Share prices continued to tumble -

124
00:11:07,249 --> 00:11:10,418
- in the aftermath of the Lehman collapse.

125
00:11:12,588 --> 00:11:14,506
The result was a global recession -

126
00:11:14,674 --> 00:11:17,550
- which cost the world tens of trillions of dollars -

127
00:11:17,718 --> 00:11:19,928
- rendered 30 million people unemployed -

128
00:11:20,096 --> 00:11:23,390
- and doubled the national debt of the United States.

129
00:11:26,310 --> 00:11:28,728
With the destruction of equity and housing wealth -

130
00:11:28,896 --> 00:11:31,398
- the destruction of income, ofjobs -

131
00:11:31,565 --> 00:11:36,986
- 50 million people globally could end up below the poverty line again.

132
00:11:37,863 --> 00:11:41,700
This is just a hugely, hugely expensive crisis.

133
00:11:42,576 --> 00:11:45,120
This crisis was not an accident.

134
00:11:45,287 --> 00:11:48,498
It was caused by an out-of-control industry.

135
00:11:48,666 --> 00:11:49,874
Since the 1 980s -

136
00:11:50,042 --> 00:11:53,128
- the rise of the U.S. financial sector has led to a series -

137
00:11:53,295 --> 00:11:56,423
- of increasingly severe financial crises.

138
00:11:56,632 --> 00:11:59,634
Each crisis has caused more damage -

139
00:11:59,802 --> 00:12:03,638
- while the industry has made more and more money.

140
00:12:11,814 --> 00:12:13,314
After the Great Depression -

141
00:12:13,482 --> 00:12:16,359
- the United States had 40 years of economic growth -

142
00:12:16,527 --> 00:12:18,820
- without a single financial crisis.

143
00:12:18,988 --> 00:12:21,865
The financial industry was tightly regulated.

144
00:12:22,032 --> 00:12:24,409
Most regular banks were local businesses -

145
00:12:24,577 --> 00:12:26,703
- prohibited from speculating -

146
00:12:26,871 --> 00:12:28,788
- with depositors' savings.

147
00:12:29,248 --> 00:12:32,208
lnvestment banks, which handled stock and bond trading -

148
00:12:32,376 --> 00:12:35,086
- were small, private partnerships.

149
00:12:35,379 --> 00:12:37,839
In the traditional investment banking model -

150
00:12:38,007 --> 00:12:39,674
- the partners put the money up -

151
00:12:42,928 --> 00:12:44,971
- and they watch that money very carefully.

152
00:12:45,139 --> 00:12:46,598
They wanted to live well -

153
00:12:46,766 --> 00:12:49,559
- but they didn't want to bet the ranch on anything.

154
00:12:49,852 --> 00:12:52,353
Paul Volcker served in the Treasury Department -

155
00:12:52,521 --> 00:12:57,442
- and was chairman of the Federal Reserve from 1 979 to 1 987.

156
00:12:57,610 --> 00:12:59,235
Before going into government -

157
00:12:59,403 --> 00:13:02,614
- he was a financial economist at Chase Manhattan Bank.

158
00:13:05,868 --> 00:13:08,411
When I left Chase to go in the Treasury in 1 969 -

159
00:13:08,579 --> 00:13:11,456
- my income was in the neighborhood of $45,000 a year.

160
00:13:11,624 --> 00:13:13,541
Forty-five thousand dollars a year.

161
00:13:13,709 --> 00:13:16,878
Morgan Stanley, in 1 972 -

162
00:13:17,046 --> 00:13:21,716
- had approximately 1 1 0 total personnel -

163
00:13:21,884 --> 00:13:26,262
- one office, and capital of 1 2 million dollars.

164
00:13:26,430 --> 00:13:30,892
Now Morgan Stanley has 50,000 workers -

165
00:13:31,060 --> 00:13:35,063
- and has capital of several billion -

166
00:13:35,231 --> 00:13:37,816
- and has offices all over the world.

167
00:13:37,983 --> 00:13:40,902
ln the 1 980s, the financial industry exploded.

168
00:13:41,070 --> 00:13:42,654
The investment banks went public -

169
00:13:42,822 --> 00:13:45,073
- giving them huge amounts of stockholder money.

170
00:13:47,034 --> 00:13:49,285
People on Wall Street started getting rich.

171
00:13:51,372 --> 00:13:53,373
I had a friend who was a bond trader -

172
00:13:56,669 --> 00:13:58,503
- at Merrill Lynch in the 1 970s.

173
00:13:58,671 --> 00:14:02,423
He had a job as a train conductor at night -

174
00:14:02,591 --> 00:14:06,052
- because he had three kids and couldn't support them -

175
00:14:06,220 --> 00:14:07,595
- on what a trader made.

176
00:14:07,763 --> 00:14:11,432
By 1 986, he was making millions of dollars -

177
00:14:11,600 --> 00:14:14,310
- and thought it was because he was smart.

178
00:14:15,062 --> 00:14:17,647
The highest order of business before the nation -

179
00:14:17,815 --> 00:14:20,191
- is to restore our economic prosperity.

180
00:14:20,359 --> 00:14:24,863
In 1 981 , President Ronald Reagan chose as Treasury secretary -

181
00:14:25,030 --> 00:14:28,533
- the CEO of the investment bank Merrill Lynch, Donald Regan.

182
00:14:28,701 --> 00:14:30,785
Wall Street and the president see eye to eye.

183
00:14:32,663 --> 00:14:34,622
I've talked to leaders of Wall Street.

184
00:14:34,790 --> 00:14:37,542
They say, "We're behind the president 1 00 percent."

185
00:14:37,710 --> 00:14:39,168
The Reagan administration -

186
00:14:39,336 --> 00:14:42,130
- supported by economists and financial lobbyists -

187
00:14:42,298 --> 00:14:46,217
- started a 30-year period of financial deregulation.

188
00:14:47,553 --> 00:14:50,138
ln 1 982, the Reagan administration -

189
00:14:50,306 --> 00:14:52,807
- deregulated savings-and-loan companies -

190
00:14:52,975 --> 00:14:56,519
- allowing them to make risky investments with depositors' money.

191
00:14:56,687 --> 00:14:58,146
By the end of the decade -

192
00:14:58,314 --> 00:15:01,399
- hundreds of savings-and-loan companies had failed.

193
00:15:01,567 --> 00:15:05,486
This crisis cost taxpayers $1 24 billion -

194
00:15:05,821 --> 00:15:08,656
- and cost many people their life savings.

195
00:15:08,824 --> 00:15:12,035
It may be the biggest bank heist in our history.

196
00:15:12,202 --> 00:15:16,414
Thousands of executives went to jail for looting their companies.

197
00:15:16,582 --> 00:15:19,167
One of the most extreme cases was Charles Keating.

198
00:15:19,335 --> 00:15:20,668
Mr. Keating, got a word?

199
00:15:20,836 --> 00:15:25,131
In 1 985, when federal regulators began investigating him -

200
00:15:25,299 --> 00:15:28,927
- Keating hired an economist named Alan Greenspan.

201
00:15:29,094 --> 00:15:30,762
In this letter to regulators -

202
00:15:30,930 --> 00:15:34,515
- Greenspan praised Keating's sound business plans and expertise -

203
00:15:34,683 --> 00:15:38,937
- and said he saw no risk in allowing Keating to invest customers' money.

204
00:15:40,648 --> 00:15:44,817
Keating reportedly paid Greenspan $40,000.

205
00:15:46,362 --> 00:15:48,863
Keating went to prison shortly afterwards.

206
00:15:49,406 --> 00:15:50,698
As for Alan Greenspan -

207
00:15:51,533 --> 00:15:54,953
- Reagan appointed him chairman of America's central bank -

208
00:15:55,120 --> 00:15:56,704
- the Federal Reserve.

209
00:15:56,872 --> 00:15:58,373
Greenspan was reappointed -

210
00:15:58,540 --> 00:16:02,251
- by presidents Clinton and George W. Bush.

211
00:16:03,087 --> 00:16:05,004
During the Clinton administration -

212
00:16:05,172 --> 00:16:07,423
- deregulation continued under Greenspan -

213
00:16:07,591 --> 00:16:10,176
- and Treasury secretaries Robert Rubin -

214
00:16:10,344 --> 00:16:13,721
- the former CEO of the investment bank Goldman Sachs -

215
00:16:13,889 --> 00:16:17,392
- and Larry Summers, a Harvard economics professor.

216
00:16:17,559 --> 00:16:20,603
The financial sector, Wall Street being powerful -

217
00:16:20,771 --> 00:16:22,730
- having lobbies, lots of money -

218
00:16:22,898 --> 00:16:26,401
- step by step, captured the political system.

219
00:16:26,568 --> 00:16:29,404
Both on the Democratic and the Republican side.

220
00:16:30,406 --> 00:16:33,950
By the late 1 990s, the financial sector had consolidated -

221
00:16:34,118 --> 00:16:37,620
- into a few gigantic firms, each of them so large -

222
00:16:37,788 --> 00:16:40,832
- that their failure could threaten the whole system.

223
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:44,585
And the Clinton administration helped them grow even larger.

224
00:16:45,170 --> 00:16:48,548
ln 1 998, Citicorp and Travelers merged -

225
00:16:48,716 --> 00:16:50,091
- to form Citigroup -

226
00:16:50,259 --> 00:16:53,094
- the largest financial services company in the world.

227
00:16:53,429 --> 00:16:55,847
The merger violated the Glass-Steagall Act -

228
00:16:56,015 --> 00:16:58,349
- a law passed after the Great Depression -

229
00:16:58,517 --> 00:17:00,852
- preventing banks with consumer deposits -

230
00:17:01,020 --> 00:17:04,272
- from engaging in risky investment-banking activities.

231
00:17:04,440 --> 00:17:06,107
It was illegal to acquire Travelers.

232
00:17:07,943 --> 00:17:09,193
Greenspan said nothing.

233
00:17:09,361 --> 00:17:12,280
The Federal Reserve gave them an exemption for a year -

234
00:17:12,448 --> 00:17:14,282
- then they got the law passed.

235
00:17:14,575 --> 00:17:18,286
ln 1 999, at the urging of Summers and Rubin -

236
00:17:18,454 --> 00:17:21,080
- Congress passed the Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act -

237
00:17:21,248 --> 00:17:24,292
- known to some as the Citigroup Relief Act.

238
00:17:24,460 --> 00:17:26,586
It overturned Glass-Steagall -

239
00:17:26,754 --> 00:17:29,756
- and cleared the way for future mergers.

240
00:17:38,307 --> 00:17:39,515
Why do you have big banks?

241
00:17:39,683 --> 00:17:42,018
Because banks like monopoly power, lobbying power.

242
00:17:44,188 --> 00:17:48,399
Because banks know that when they're too big -

243
00:17:48,567 --> 00:17:49,817
- they will be bailed.

244
00:17:49,985 --> 00:17:51,527
Markets are inherently unstable.

245
00:17:53,489 --> 00:17:55,073
Or at least potentially unstable.

246
00:17:55,240 --> 00:17:59,077
An appropriate metaphor is the oil tankers.

247
00:17:59,244 --> 00:18:00,536
They are very big -

248
00:18:00,871 --> 00:18:03,581
- and therefore, you have to put in compartments -

249
00:18:04,041 --> 00:18:07,251
- to prevent the sloshing around of oil -

250
00:18:07,419 --> 00:18:09,253
- from capsizing the boat.

251
00:18:09,421 --> 00:18:12,757
The design of the boat has to take that into account.

252
00:18:12,925 --> 00:18:15,885
And after the Depression -

253
00:18:16,053 --> 00:18:21,766
- the regulations actually introduced these very watertight compartments.

254
00:18:22,392 --> 00:18:28,231
And deregulation has led to the end of compartmentalization.

255
00:18:29,024 --> 00:18:31,275
The next crisis came at the end of the '90s.

256
00:18:32,653 --> 00:18:35,738
