It saved him $50 million.

756
00:49:38,725 --> 00:49:42,353
The article came out in October of 2007.

757
00:49:42,688 --> 00:49:46,232
Already, a third of the mortgages defaulted.

758
00:49:46,400 --> 00:49:48,818
Now most of them are going.

759
00:49:51,071 --> 00:49:54,281
One group that had purchased these now worthless securities -

760
00:49:54,449 --> 00:49:57,952
- was the Public Employees' Retirement System of Mississippi -

761
00:49:58,120 --> 00:50:01,664
- which provides monthly benefits to over 80,000 retirees.

762
00:50:02,582 --> 00:50:07,420
They lost millions of dollars and are now suing Goldman Sachs.

763
00:50:21,393 --> 00:50:25,730
By late 2006, Goldman had taken things a step further.

764
00:50:25,897 --> 00:50:28,399
It didn't just sell toxic CDOs -

765
00:50:28,567 --> 00:50:32,737
- it started betting against them at the same time it was telling customers -

766
00:50:32,904 --> 00:50:35,614
- that they were high-quality investments.

767
00:50:36,533 --> 00:50:39,785
By purchasing credit default swaps from AlG -

768
00:50:39,953 --> 00:50:42,955
- Goldman could bet against CDOs it didn't own -

769
00:50:43,123 --> 00:50:46,333
- and get paid when the CDOs failed.

770
00:50:47,294 --> 00:50:51,505
I asked if anybody called the customers and said:

771
00:50:51,673 --> 00:50:54,467
"We don't really like this kind of mortgage anymore -

772
00:50:54,634 --> 00:50:56,802
- and we thought you ought to know."

773
00:50:56,970 --> 00:51:01,515
They didn't say anything, but you could feel the laughter over the phone.

774
00:51:03,226 --> 00:51:05,644
Goldman Sachs bought at least $22 billion -

775
00:51:05,812 --> 00:51:08,439
- of credit default swaps from AIG.

776
00:51:08,607 --> 00:51:13,486
lt was so much that Goldman realized that AlG itself might go bankrupt.

777
00:51:13,653 --> 00:51:16,655
So they spent $1 50 million insuring themselves -

778
00:51:16,823 --> 00:51:19,617
- against AIG's potential collapse.

779
00:51:19,785 --> 00:51:23,370
Then in 2007, Goldman went even further.

780
00:51:23,538 --> 00:51:26,248
They started selling CDOs specifically designed -

781
00:51:26,416 --> 00:51:28,959
- so that the more money their customers lost -

782
00:51:29,127 --> 00:51:31,420
- the more money Goldman Sachs made.

783
00:51:38,178 --> 00:51:41,597
Six hundred million dollars of Timberwolf securities is what you sold.

784
00:51:44,518 --> 00:51:45,768
Before you sold them -

785
00:51:45,936 --> 00:51:49,271
- this is what your sales team were telling to each other:

786
00:51:50,065 --> 00:51:53,776
"Boy, that Timberwolf was one shitty deal."

787
00:51:53,944 --> 00:51:57,029
This was an e-mail to me in late June, after the transaction.

788
00:52:00,367 --> 00:52:02,535
No, no. You sold Timberwolf after as well.

789
00:52:02,702 --> 00:52:04,912
-We did trades after that. -Yeah. Okay.

790
00:52:05,205 --> 00:52:08,415
The next e-mail-- Take a look. July 1 , '07.

791
00:52:08,583 --> 00:52:11,752
--tells the sales force, "The top priority is Timberwolf."

792
00:52:12,045 --> 00:52:15,381
Your top priority to sell is that shitty deal.

793
00:52:15,549 --> 00:52:17,800
If you have an adverse interest to your client -

794
00:52:17,968 --> 00:52:19,802
- do you have the duty to disclose it?

795
00:52:19,970 --> 00:52:22,304
To tell that client of your adverse interest?

796
00:52:22,472 --> 00:52:24,974
-That's my question. -l'm trying to understand--

797
00:52:25,142 --> 00:52:27,643
I think you understand. You don't wanna answer.

798
00:52:27,811 --> 00:52:29,353
Do you believe you have a duty -

799
00:52:32,149 --> 00:52:34,066
- to act in your clients' best interest?

800
00:52:38,071 --> 00:52:40,281
I repeat, we have a duty to serve our clients -

801
00:52:40,448 --> 00:52:44,910
- by showing prices on transactions that they ask us to show prices for.

802
00:52:45,078 --> 00:52:47,872
What do you think about selling securities -

803
00:52:48,039 --> 00:52:51,167
- which your own people think are crap?

804
00:52:51,334 --> 00:52:53,085
Does that bother you?

805
00:52:53,253 --> 00:52:54,920
I think they would - .

806
00:52:56,756 --> 00:52:58,507
-As a hypothetical? -No, this is real.

807
00:52:58,675 --> 00:53:01,093
-Well, then I don't know-- -We heard it today.

808
00:53:01,261 --> 00:53:04,305
We heard it today. "This is a shitty deal." "This is crap."

809
00:53:04,472 --> 00:53:06,515
I heard nothing today -

810
00:53:06,683 --> 00:53:10,436
- that makes me think anything went wrong.

811
00:53:10,604 --> 00:53:14,690
Is there not a conflict when you sell something to somebody -

812
00:53:14,858 --> 00:53:20,279
- and then are determined to bet against that same security -

813
00:53:20,447 --> 00:53:24,033
- and you don't disclose that to the person you're selling it to?

814
00:53:24,201 --> 00:53:25,242
You see a problem?

815
00:53:25,410 --> 00:53:28,495
In the context of market making, that is not a conflict.

816
00:53:32,125 --> 00:53:35,502
When you heard your employees in e-mails said, "What a shitty deal" -

817
00:53:35,670 --> 00:53:37,046
- did you feel anything?

818
00:53:37,214 --> 00:53:39,548
That's very unfortunate to have on e-mail.

819
00:53:39,716 --> 00:53:41,008
Are you embar--?

820
00:53:41,176 --> 00:53:44,053
And very unfortunate-- I don't-- I don't--

821
00:53:44,221 --> 00:53:46,972
"On e-mail"? How about feeling that way?

822
00:53:47,140 --> 00:53:50,517
It's very unfortunate for anyone to have said that in any form.

823
00:53:53,271 --> 00:53:55,731
Are your competitors engaged in similar activities?

824
00:53:55,899 --> 00:53:59,693
Yes, and to a greater extent than us in most cases.

825
00:54:00,070 --> 00:54:03,530
Hedge fund manager John Paulson made $1 2 billion -

826
00:54:03,698 --> 00:54:05,741
- betting against the mortgage market.

827
00:54:05,909 --> 00:54:09,119
When Paulson ran out of mortgage securities to bet against -

828
00:54:09,287 --> 00:54:13,749
- he worked with Goldman Sachs and Deutsche Bank to create more.

829
00:54:14,167 --> 00:54:15,751
Morgan Stanley was also selling -

830
00:54:15,919 --> 00:54:19,672
- mortgage securities it was betting against, and it's now being sued by -

831
00:54:19,839 --> 00:54:23,342
- the Government Employees' Retirement Fund of the Virgin Islands -

832
00:54:23,510 --> 00:54:24,718
- for fraud.

833
00:54:24,886 --> 00:54:27,346
The lawsuit alleges that Morgan Stanley knew -

834
00:54:27,514 --> 00:54:29,139
- that the CDOs were junk.

835
00:54:29,307 --> 00:54:31,225
Although they were rated triple-A -

836
00:54:31,393 --> 00:54:34,019
- Morgan Stanley was betting they would fail.

837
00:54:34,187 --> 00:54:38,399
A year later, Morgan Stanley had made hundreds of millions of dollars -

838
00:54:38,566 --> 00:54:42,528
- while the investors had lost almost all of their money.

839
00:54:58,545 --> 00:55:01,297
You would have thought pension funds would have said:

840
00:55:01,464 --> 00:55:05,009
"Those are subprime. Why am l buying them?"

841
00:55:05,719 --> 00:55:08,721
They had these guys at Moody's and Standard & Poor's -

842
00:55:08,888 --> 00:55:10,597
- who said, "That's a triple-A."

843
00:55:12,600 --> 00:55:16,812
No securities got issued without the seal of approval of the rating agencies.

844
00:55:18,231 --> 00:55:21,734
The three rating agencies, Moody's, S&P and Fitch -

845
00:55:21,901 --> 00:55:25,571
- made billions of dollars giving high ratings to risky securities.

846
00:55:26,990 --> 00:55:30,200
Moody's, the largest rating agency, quadrupled its profits -

847
00:55:30,368 --> 00:55:33,620
- between 2000 and 2007.

848
00:55:34,039 --> 00:55:37,624
Moody's and S&P get compensated based on putting out ratings reports.

849
00:55:37,792 --> 00:55:41,420
And the more structured securities they gave a triple-A rating to -

850
00:55:41,588 --> 00:55:43,422
- the higher their earnings were.

851
00:55:43,590 --> 00:55:45,382
Imagine going to The Times saying:

852
00:55:45,550 --> 00:55:47,968
"Write a positive story, I'll pay you $500,000.

853
00:55:48,136 --> 00:55:50,095
If you don't, l'll give you nothing."

854
00:55:50,263 --> 00:55:52,765
Rating agencies could have stopped the party and said:

855
00:55:52,932 --> 00:55:54,975
"Sorry. We're gonna tighten our standards" -

856
00:55:58,104 --> 00:56:01,023
- and immediately cut off the funding to risky borrowers.

857
00:56:01,191 --> 00:56:03,609
Triple-A-rated instruments -

858
00:56:05,195 --> 00:56:11,033
- mushroomed from just a handful to thousands and thousands.

859
00:56:11,201 --> 00:56:15,621
Hundreds of billions of dollars were being rated, you know, and--

860
00:56:15,789 --> 00:56:17,664
-Per year? -Per year. Oh, yeah.

861
00:56:17,832 --> 00:56:20,918
I've now testified before both houses of Congress -

862
00:56:21,086 --> 00:56:24,338
- on the credit rating agency issue -

863
00:56:24,506 --> 00:56:28,967
- and both times they trot out very prominent First Amendment lawyers -

864
00:56:29,135 --> 00:56:33,305
- and argue that, "When we say something is rated triple-A -

865
00:56:33,473 --> 00:56:37,142
- that is merely our 'opinion.' You shouldn't rely on it."

866
00:56:37,310 --> 00:56:39,478
S&P's ratings express our opinion.

867
00:56:39,646 --> 00:56:42,856
Our ratings are our opinions. They're opinions.

868
00:56:43,108 --> 00:56:45,317
Opinions. And they are just opinions.

869
00:56:45,485 --> 00:56:49,905
I think we are emphasizing the fact that our ratings are opinions.

870
00:56:56,204 --> 00:56:58,997
They do not speak to the market value of a security -

871
00:56:59,165 --> 00:57:03,710
- the volatility of its price, or its suitability as an investment.

872
00:57:23,481 --> 00:57:25,107
We have many economists saying:

873
00:57:25,275 --> 00:57:27,276
"This is a bubble, it's going to burst.

874
00:57:27,444 --> 00:57:29,862
This is going to be an issue for the economy."

875
00:57:30,029 --> 00:57:32,865
Some say it could even cause a recession at some point.

876
00:57:33,032 --> 00:57:36,994
What is the worst-case scenario if, in fact, we were to see prices -

877
00:57:37,162 --> 00:57:39,913
- come down substantially across the country?

878
00:57:40,081 --> 00:57:43,208
I don't buy your premise. It's an unlikely possibility.

879
00:57:43,376 --> 00:57:47,754
We've never had a decline in house prices on a nationwide basis.

880
00:57:47,922 --> 00:57:52,426
Ben Bernanke became chairman of the Federal Reserve in February 2006 -

881
00:57:52,594 --> 00:57:54,470
- the top year for subprime lending.

882
00:57:56,264 --> 00:57:58,098
But despite numerous warnings -

883
00:57:58,266 --> 00:58:01,393
- Bernanke and the Federal Reserve Board did nothing.

884
00:58:05,982 --> 00:58:09,359
Robert Gnaizda met with Bernanke and the Federal Reserve Board -

885
00:58:09,527 --> 00:58:12,654
- three times after Bernanke became chairman.

886
00:58:12,822 --> 00:58:17,784
Only at the last meeting did he suggest that there was a problem -

887
00:58:17,952 --> 00:58:20,245
- and that the government ought to look into it.

888
00:58:20,413 --> 00:58:22,247
When? When was that? What year?

889
00:58:22,415 --> 00:58:25,542
It's 2009, March 1 1th, in D.C.

890
00:58:25,710 --> 00:58:27,503
-This year? -This year we met, yes.

891
00:58:27,670 --> 00:58:30,214
And so for the two previous years you met him - .

892
00:58:30,381 --> 00:58:33,008
-Even in 2008? -Yes.

893
00:58:33,176 --> 00:58:37,012
One of the six Federal Reserve Board governors serving under Bernanke -

894
00:58:37,180 --> 00:58:38,597
- was Frederic Mishkin -

895
00:58:38,765 --> 00:58:42,267
- who was appointed by President Bush in 2006.

896
00:58:43,978 --> 00:58:46,480
Did you participate in the meetings Robert Gnaizda -

897
00:58:46,648 --> 00:58:49,441
- and Greenlining had with the Federal Reserve Board?

898
00:58:49,609 --> 00:58:52,486
Yes, l did. I was on the committee that was involved -

899
00:58:52,654 --> 00:58:55,239
- with the Consumer Community Affairs Committee.

900
00:58:55,406 --> 00:58:59,243
He warned, in an extremely explicit manner, about what was going on.

901
00:58:59,410 --> 00:59:02,704
He came to the Federal Reserve Board with loan documentation -

902
00:59:02,872 --> 00:59:05,791
- of the kind of loans that were frequently being made.

903
00:59:05,959 --> 00:59:08,794
And he was listened to politely, and nothing was done.

904
00:59:08,962 --> 00:59:14,508
So again, l don't know the details in terms of - .

905
00:59:14,968 --> 00:59:17,636
In fact, l just don't-- l--

906
00:59:17,804 --> 00:59:21,557
Whatever information he provided, I'm not sure exactly - .

907
00:59:21,933 --> 00:59:25,394
To be honest with you, I can't remember this kind of discussion -

908
00:59:25,562 --> 00:59:30,399
- but certainly there were issues that were coming up.

909
00:59:30,567 --> 00:59:32,859
The question is, how pervasive are they?

910
00:59:33,027 --> 00:59:36,154
-Why didn't you try looking? -l think that people did.

911
00:59:36,322 --> 00:59:37,906
We had people looking at--

912
00:59:38,074 --> 00:59:41,326
Excuse me. You can't be serious. You would have found things.

913
00:59:41,494 --> 00:59:45,831
That's very easy to always say that you can always find it.

914
00:59:45,999 --> 00:59:47,708
As early as 2004 -

915
00:59:47,875 --> 00:59:52,170
- the FBI was already warning about an epidemic of mortgage fraud.

916
00:59:52,338 --> 00:59:54,631
They reported inflated appraisals -

917
00:59:54,799 --> 00:59:58,427
- doctored loan documentation and other fraudulent activity.

918
00:59:59,554 --> 01:00:03,807
ln 2005, the IMF's chief economist, Raghuram Rajan -

919
01:00:03,975 --> 01:00:07,603
- warned that dangerous incentives could lead to a crisis.

920
01:00:08,146 --> 01:00:11,690
Then came Nouriel Roubini's warnings in 2006 -

921
01:00:11,858 --> 01:00:14,359
- Allan Sloan's articles in Fortune magazine -

922
01:00:14,527 --> 01:00:16,612
- and The Washington Post in 2007 -

923
01:00:17,155 --> 01:00:19,573
- and repeated warnings from the lMF.

924
01:00:19,741 --> 01:00:25,537
I said, and on behalf of the institution, the crisis in front of us is a huge crisis.

925
01:00:25,705 --> 01:00:26,747
Who did you talk to?

926
01:00:26,914 --> 01:00:29,082
The government, Treasury, Fed, everybody.

927
01:00:29,250 --> 01:00:35,088
In May of 2007, hedge fund manager Bill Ackman circulated a presentation -

928
01:00:35,256 --> 01:00:36,882
- "Who is Holding the Bag?" -

929
01:00:37,050 --> 01:00:39,885
- which described how the bubble would unravel.

930
01:00:40,428 --> 01:00:43,722
And in early 2008, Charles Morris published his book -

931
01:00:43,890 --> 01:00:45,474
- about the impending crisis.

932
01:00:48,269 --> 01:00:50,520
You're not sure. What do you do?

933
01:00:50,688 --> 01:00:54,858
You might have some suspicions that underwriting standards are weakened.

934
01:00:55,026 --> 01:00:58,487
But then the question is, should you do anything about it?

935
01:00:59,906 --> 01:01:03,575
By 2008, home foreclosures were skyrocketing -

936
01:01:03,743 --> 01:01:06,912
- and the securitization food chain imploded.

937
01:01:07,080 --> 01:01:10,540
Lenders could no longer sell their loans to the investment banks.

938
01:01:10,708 --> 01:01:14,169
And as the loans went bad, dozens of lenders failed.

939
01:01:15,588 --> 01:01:20,300
Chuck Prince of Citibank famously said -

940
01:01:21,469 --> 01:01:24,388
- that we have to dance until the music stops.

941
01:01:24,555 --> 01:01:27,849
Actually, the music had stopped already when he said that.

942
01:01:28,017 --> 01:01:30,477
The market for CDOs collapsed -

943
01:01:30,645 --> 01:01:33,980
- leaving investment banks holding hundreds of billions of dollars -

944
01:01:34,148 --> 01:01:38,360
- in loans, CDOs, and real estate they couldn't sell.

945
01:01:38,528 --> 01:01:42,114
When the crisis started, both the Bush administration -

946
01:01:42,281 --> 01:01:46,618
- and the Federal Reserve were totally behind the curve.

947
01:01:46,786 --> 01:01:49,121
They did not understand the extent of it.

948
01:01:49,372 --> 01:01:53,375
At what point do you remember thinking for the first time:

949
01:01:53,543 --> 01:01:55,877
"This is dangerous, this is bad"?

950
01:01:56,045 --> 01:02:00,215
I remember very well one-- I think it was a G7 meeting -

951
01:02:00,383 --> 01:02:02,384
- of February, 2008.

952
01:02:02,552 --> 01:02:06,471
And l remember discussing the issue with Hank Paulson.

953
01:02:06,639 --> 01:02:09,683
And l clearly remember telling Hank:

954
01:02:09,851 --> 01:02:12,853
"We are watching this tsunami coming -

955
01:02:13,020 --> 01:02:16,773
- and you're just proposing that we ask -

956
01:02:16,941 --> 01:02:19,526
- which swimming costume we're going to put on."

957
01:02:19,694 --> 01:02:22,028
What was his response? What was his feeling?

958
01:02:22,196 --> 01:02:23,613
"Things are under control.

959
01:02:23,781 --> 01:02:27,743
Yes, we are looking at this situation carefully -

960
01:02:27,910 --> 01:02:31,329
- and, yeah, it's under control."

961
01:02:33,791 --> 01:02:36,585
We're gonna keep growing. Okay? And, obviously, I'll say it:

962
01:02:36,753 --> 01:02:39,337
If you're growing, you're not in recession, right?

963
01:02:39,505 --> 01:02:41,506
I mean, we all know that.

964
01:02:46,721 --> 01:02:48,764
One of the pillars of Wall Street - .

965
01:02:48,931 --> 01:02:53,185
ln March 2008, the investment bank Bear Stearns ran out of cash -

966
01:02:53,853 --> 01:02:57,564
- and was acquired for $2 a share by JPMorgan Chase.

967
01:02:57,732 --> 01:03:01,401
The deal was backed by $30 billion in emergency guarantees -

968
01:03:01,569 --> 01:03:03,028
- from the Federal Reserve.

969
01:03:04,572 --> 01:03:07,157
That was when the administration could have come in -

970
01:03:10,578 --> 01:03:13,288
- and put in place various measures to reduce system risk.

971
01:03:14,749 --> 01:03:18,335
The information I'm receiving is the end is not here -

972
01:03:18,503 --> 01:03:20,712
- that there are other shoes to fall.

973
01:03:20,880 --> 01:03:23,215
Well, l've seen those investment banks -

974
01:03:24,550 --> 01:03:27,177
- working with the Fed and the SEC -

975
01:03:27,345 --> 01:03:33,391
- strengthen their liquidity, strengthen their capital positions.

976
01:03:33,559 --> 01:03:37,646
I get reports all the time. Our regulators are very vigilant.

977
01:03:38,314 --> 01:03:40,232
On September 7th, 2008 -

978
01:03:40,399 --> 01:03:42,984
- Henry Paulson announced the federal takeover -

979
01:03:43,152 --> 01:03:47,739
- of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, giant lenders on the brink of collapse.

980
01:03:49,075 --> 01:03:52,118
Nothing about our actions today reflects a changed view -

981
01:03:52,286 --> 01:03:53,912
- of the housing correction -

982
01:03:54,080 --> 01:03:57,123
- or the strength of other U.S. financial institutions.

983
01:03:57,375 --> 01:03:58,416
Two days later -

984
01:03:58,584 --> 01:04:02,254
- Lehman Brothers announced record losses of $3.2 billion -

985
01:04:02,421 --> 01:04:03,839
- and its stock collapsed.

986
01:04:05,508 --> 01:04:09,928
The effects of Lehman and AlG in September still came as a surprise.

987
01:04:10,096 --> 01:04:13,557
I mean, this is even after July and Fannie and Freddie.

988
01:04:13,724 --> 01:04:18,603
So clearly there was stuff that, as of September -

989
01:04:18,771 --> 01:04:22,649
- major stuff, that nobody knew about.

990
01:04:22,817 --> 01:04:25,026
I think that's-- l think that's fair.

991
01:04:25,194 --> 01:04:29,573
Bear Stearns was rated triple-A like a month before it went bankrupt?

992
01:04:29,740 --> 01:04:31,783
-More likely A2. -A2?

993
01:04:31,951 --> 01:04:33,076
-Yeah. -Okay.

994
01:04:33,244 --> 01:04:34,995
A2 is still not bankrupt.

995
01:04:35,162 --> 01:04:38,665
No, that's a high investment grade. Solid investment grade rating.

996
01:04:38,833 --> 01:04:41,918
Lehman Brothers, A2 within days of failing.

