01:20:05,550 --> 01:20:07,510
I attended a very interesting dinner -

1236
01:20:07,677 --> 01:20:11,347
- organized by Hank Paulson a little more than one year ago -

1237
01:20:11,515 --> 01:20:14,141
- with some officials and a couple of CEOs -

1238
01:20:14,309 --> 01:20:16,560
- from the biggest banks in the U.S.

1239
01:20:16,728 --> 01:20:21,065
And surprisingly enough, all these gentlemen were arguing:

1240
01:20:21,233 --> 01:20:25,236
"We were too greedy, so we have part of the responsibility." Fine.

1241
01:20:25,403 --> 01:20:29,198
Then they were turning to the treasurer, Secretary of the Treasury, and saying:

1242
01:20:29,366 --> 01:20:32,535
"You should regulate more. We're too greedy, we can't avoid it.

1243
01:20:32,702 --> 01:20:35,663
The only way to avoid this is to have more regulation."

1244
01:20:35,831 --> 01:20:38,749
I have spoken to many bankers about this question -

1245
01:20:38,917 --> 01:20:40,835
- including very senior ones.

1246
01:20:41,002 --> 01:20:45,798
And this is the first time that I've ever heard anybody say -

1247
01:20:45,966 --> 01:20:49,009
- they wanted their compensation to be regulated in any way.

1248
01:20:49,177 --> 01:20:52,388
Yeah, because it was at the moment where they were afraid.

1249
01:20:52,556 --> 01:20:56,851
And after, when solution to the crisis began to appear -

1250
01:20:57,018 --> 01:20:59,270
- then probably they changed their mind.

1251
01:21:01,690 --> 01:21:05,526
In the U.S., the banks are now bigger, more powerful -

1252
01:21:05,694 --> 01:21:08,779
- and more concentrated than ever before.

1253
01:21:08,947 --> 01:21:10,781
There are fewer competitors.

1254
01:21:10,949 --> 01:21:14,952
A lot of smaller banks have been taken over by big ones.

1255
01:21:15,120 --> 01:21:17,538
J.P. Morgan is even bigger than it was before.

1256
01:21:17,706 --> 01:21:21,667
J.P. Morgan took over first Bear Stearns and then WaMu.

1257
01:21:21,835 --> 01:21:25,671
Bank of America took over Countrywide and Merrill Lynch.

1258
01:21:25,839 --> 01:21:28,340
Wells Fargo took over Wachovia.

1259
01:21:28,508 --> 01:21:30,801
After the crisis, the financial industry -

1260
01:21:30,969 --> 01:21:33,804
- including the Financial Services Roundtable -

1261
01:21:33,972 --> 01:21:36,473
- worked harder than ever to fight reform.

1262
01:21:36,641 --> 01:21:39,310
The financial sector employs 3000 lobbyists -

1263
01:21:39,853 --> 01:21:43,314
- more than five for each member of Congress.

1264
01:21:43,815 --> 01:21:45,816
You think the financial services industry -

1265
01:21:45,984 --> 01:21:48,652
- has excessive political influence in the United States?

1266
01:21:48,820 --> 01:21:53,240
No. I think that every person in the country -

1267
01:21:53,408 --> 01:21:55,200
- is represented here in Washington.

1268
01:21:55,368 --> 01:21:59,121
And you think that all segments of American society -

1269
01:21:59,289 --> 01:22:02,625
- have equal and fair access to the system?

1270
01:22:02,792 --> 01:22:07,671
That you can walk into any hearing room that you would like. Yes, l do.

1271
01:22:07,923 --> 01:22:11,133
One can walk into any hearing room. One cannot necessarily -

1272
01:22:11,301 --> 01:22:14,136
- write the lobbying checks that your industry writes -

1273
01:22:14,304 --> 01:22:18,098
- or engage in the level of political contributions your industry engages in.

1274
01:22:18,391 --> 01:22:21,268
Between 1 998 and 2008 -

1275
01:22:21,436 --> 01:22:24,355
- the financial industry spent over $5 billion -

1276
01:22:24,522 --> 01:22:27,024
- on lobbying and campaign contributions.

1277
01:22:27,192 --> 01:22:30,069
And since the crisis, they're spending even more money.

1278
01:22:31,821 --> 01:22:34,281
The financial industry also exerts its influence -

1279
01:22:34,449 --> 01:22:38,369
- in a more subtle way, one that most Americans don't know about.

1280
01:22:39,996 --> 01:22:42,539
It has corrupted the study of economics itself.

1281
01:22:44,042 --> 01:22:50,089
Deregulation had tremendous financial and intellectual support -

1282
01:22:50,256 --> 01:22:54,718
- because people argued it for their own benefit.

1283
01:22:54,886 --> 01:22:59,556
The economics profession was the main source of that illusion.

1284
01:22:59,891 --> 01:23:02,935
Since the 1 980s, academic economists -

1285
01:23:03,103 --> 01:23:05,562
- have been major advocates of deregulation -

1286
01:23:05,730 --> 01:23:09,108
- and played powerful roles in shaping U.S. government policy.

1287
01:23:09,693 --> 01:23:13,445
Very few of these economic experts warned about the crisis.

1288
01:23:13,613 --> 01:23:18,158
And even after the crisis, many of them opposed reform.

1289
01:23:18,410 --> 01:23:22,287
The guys who taught these things tended to get paid a lot of money -

1290
01:23:22,455 --> 01:23:24,581
- being consultants.

1291
01:23:24,749 --> 01:23:29,336
Business school professors don't live on a faculty salary.

1292
01:23:30,422 --> 01:23:33,090
They do very, very well.

1293
01:23:33,550 --> 01:23:36,301
Over the last decade, the financial services industries -

1294
01:23:38,847 --> 01:23:42,725
- made about $5 billion worth of political contributions in the U.S.

1295
01:23:43,768 --> 01:23:46,103
That's kind of a lot of money.

1296
01:23:46,604 --> 01:23:49,273
-That doesn't bother you? -No.

1297
01:23:49,441 --> 01:23:51,942
Martin Feldstein is a professor at Harvard -

1298
01:23:52,110 --> 01:23:54,528
- and one of the world's most prominent economists.

1299
01:23:54,904 --> 01:23:57,698
As President Reagan's chief economic advisor -

1300
01:23:57,866 --> 01:24:00,284
- he was a major architect of deregulation.

1301
01:24:00,452 --> 01:24:03,495
And from 1 988 until 2009 -

1302
01:24:03,788 --> 01:24:06,915
- he was on the board of directors of both AlG -

1303
01:24:07,083 --> 01:24:09,043
- and AlG Financial Products -

1304
01:24:09,210 --> 01:24:11,462
- which paid him millions of dollars.

1305
01:24:11,713 --> 01:24:14,590
You have any regrets about having been on AlG's board?

1306
01:24:14,758 --> 01:24:18,427
I have no comments. No, I have no regrets about being on AlG's board.

1307
01:24:18,595 --> 01:24:22,014
-None? -That I can say. Absolutely none.

1308
01:24:22,182 --> 01:24:23,640
Okay.

1309
01:24:26,061 --> 01:24:30,773
You have any regrets about AlG's decisions?

1310
01:24:30,940 --> 01:24:33,692
I cannot say anything more about AlG.

1311
01:24:33,860 --> 01:24:37,946
I've taught at Northwestern in Chicago, Harvard and Columbia.

1312
01:24:38,114 --> 01:24:41,033
Glenn Hubbard is the dean of Columbia Business School -

1313
01:24:41,201 --> 01:24:43,911
- and was chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers -

1314
01:24:44,079 --> 01:24:46,080
- under George W. Bush.

1315
01:24:46,247 --> 01:24:48,373
Do you think the financial services industry -

1316
01:24:48,541 --> 01:24:51,960
- has too much political power in the United States?

1317
01:24:52,420 --> 01:24:56,548
I don't think so. No. You certainly wouldn't get that impression -

1318
01:24:56,716 --> 01:25:00,511
- by the drubbing that they regularly get in Washington.

1319
01:25:00,678 --> 01:25:03,514
Many prominent academics quietly make fortunes -

1320
01:25:03,681 --> 01:25:08,519
- helping the financial industry shape public debate and government policy.

1321
01:25:08,686 --> 01:25:11,939
The Analysis Group, Charles River Associates -

1322
01:25:12,107 --> 01:25:13,440
- Compass Lexecon -

1323
01:25:13,608 --> 01:25:15,859
- and the Law and Economics Consulting Group -

1324
01:25:16,027 --> 01:25:18,237
- manage a multibillion-dollar industry -

1325
01:25:18,404 --> 01:25:21,698
- that provides academic experts for hire.

1326
01:25:21,866 --> 01:25:23,867
Two bankers who used these services -

1327
01:25:24,035 --> 01:25:27,079
- were Ralph Cioffi and Matthew Tannin -

1328
01:25:27,247 --> 01:25:31,208
- Bear Stearns hedge fund managers prosecuted for securities fraud.

1329
01:25:31,376 --> 01:25:34,545
After hiring the Analysis Group, both were acquitted.

1330
01:25:34,879 --> 01:25:40,134
Glenn Hubbard was paid $1 00,000 to testify in their defense.

1331
01:25:40,802 --> 01:25:46,640
Do you think the economics discipline has a conflict-of-interest problem?

1332
01:25:47,684 --> 01:25:49,268
I'm not sure l know what you mean.

1333
01:25:49,435 --> 01:25:53,730
Do you think a significant fraction of the economics discipline, economists -

1334
01:25:53,898 --> 01:25:59,069
- have financial conflicts of interest that might call into question or color--?

1335
01:25:59,237 --> 01:26:01,238
I see what you're saying. I doubt it.

1336
01:26:01,406 --> 01:26:06,577
Most academic economists aren't wealthy business people.

1337
01:26:06,744 --> 01:26:10,914
Hubbard makes $250,000 a year as a board member of MetLife -

1338
01:26:11,082 --> 01:26:13,500
- and was formerly on the board of Capmark -

1339
01:26:13,668 --> 01:26:16,712
- a major commercial mortgage lender during the bubble -

1340
01:26:16,880 --> 01:26:18,922
- which went bankrupt in 2009.

1341
01:26:19,090 --> 01:26:21,466
He has also advised Nomura Securities -

1342
01:26:21,634 --> 01:26:26,054
- KKR Financial Corporation and many other financial firms.

1343
01:26:27,348 --> 01:26:30,475
Laura Tyson, who declined to be interviewed for this film -

1344
01:26:30,643 --> 01:26:34,438
- is a professor at the University of California, Berkeley.

1345
01:26:34,606 --> 01:26:37,816
She was the chair of the Council of Economic Advisers -

1346
01:26:37,984 --> 01:26:41,445
- then director of the National Economic Council under Clinton.

1347
01:26:41,613 --> 01:26:45,282
After leaving government, she joined the board of Morgan Stanley -

1348
01:26:45,450 --> 01:26:48,994
- which pays her $350,000 a year.

1349
01:26:49,162 --> 01:26:51,663
Ruth Simmons, president of Brown University -

1350
01:26:51,831 --> 01:26:56,919
- makes over $300,000 a year on the board of Goldman Sachs.

1351
01:26:57,128 --> 01:27:00,172
Larry Summers, who, as Treasury secretary, played a role -

1352
01:27:00,340 --> 01:27:05,677
- in the deregulation of derivatives, became president of Harvard in 2001 .

1353
01:27:06,012 --> 01:27:09,348
While at Harvard, he made millions consulting to hedge funds -

1354
01:27:09,515 --> 01:27:13,894
- and millions more in speaking fees, much of it from investment banks.

1355
01:27:16,648 --> 01:27:20,025
According to his federal disclosure report, Summers' net worth -

1356
01:27:20,193 --> 01:27:25,239
- is between $1 6.5 million and $39.5 million.

1357
01:27:25,990 --> 01:27:28,825
Frederic Mishkin, who returned to Columbia Business School -

1358
01:27:28,993 --> 01:27:33,121
- after leaving the Federal Reserve, reported on his disclosure report -

1359
01:27:33,289 --> 01:27:37,668
- that his net worth was between $6 million and $17 million.

1360
01:27:38,127 --> 01:27:42,547
In 2006, you coauthored a study of lceland's financial system.

1361
01:27:42,757 --> 01:27:44,549
"Iceland is an advanced country -

1362
01:27:44,717 --> 01:27:47,928
- with excellent institutions, low corruption, rule of law.

1363
01:27:48,096 --> 01:27:51,098
The economy has adjusted to financial liberalization -

1364
01:27:51,266 --> 01:27:55,519
- while prudential regulation and supervision is generally quite strong."

1365
01:27:55,687 --> 01:27:58,397
And that was the mistake, that it turns out -

1366
01:27:58,564 --> 01:28:02,025
- prudential regulation and supervision was not strong in lceland -

1367
01:28:02,193 --> 01:28:05,070
- - during this period-- -What led you to think it was?

1368
01:28:05,238 --> 01:28:07,531
You're going with the information you had -

1369
01:28:07,699 --> 01:28:13,203
- and generally, the view was that Iceland had very good institutions.

1370
01:28:13,371 --> 01:28:15,872
-lt was an advanced country-- -Who told you that?

1371
01:28:16,040 --> 01:28:18,458
-What research did you do? -You talk to people.

1372
01:28:18,626 --> 01:28:23,213
You have faith in the central bank, which actually did fall down on the job.

1373
01:28:23,381 --> 01:28:25,841
That clearly it-- This--

1374
01:28:26,009 --> 01:28:29,553
-Why have faith in a central bank? -Well, that faith-- You try--

1375
01:28:29,721 --> 01:28:31,888
Because you go with the information you have.

1376
01:28:32,056 --> 01:28:34,683
-How much were you paid to write it? -l was paid--

1377
01:28:34,851 --> 01:28:37,227
I think the number-- It's public information.

1378
01:28:44,819 --> 01:28:47,904
On your CV, the title of this report has been changed -

1379
01:28:48,072 --> 01:28:52,242
- from "Financial Stability in lceland" to "Financial lnstability in Iceland."

1380
01:28:52,410 --> 01:28:56,955
Well, l don't know. Whatever it is-- If there's a typo, there's a typo.

1381
01:28:57,123 --> 01:28:58,999
What should be publicly available -

1382
01:28:59,167 --> 01:29:01,585
- is whenever anybody does research on a topic -

1383
01:29:01,753 --> 01:29:06,465
- that they disclose if they have any financial conflict with that research.

1384
01:29:06,632 --> 01:29:10,635
But if I recall, there is no policy to that effect.

1385
01:29:11,179 --> 01:29:16,641
I can't imagine anybody not doing that in terms of putting it in a paper. You--

1386
01:29:16,809 --> 01:29:20,437
There would be significant professional sanction for failure to do that.

1387
01:29:20,605 --> 01:29:25,233
I didn't see any place in the study where you indicated you'd been paid -

1388
01:29:25,401 --> 01:29:28,695
- by the lcelandic Chamber of Commerce to produce it.

1389
01:29:28,863 --> 01:29:31,656
-No, I don't-- You know. -Okay.

1390
01:29:32,033 --> 01:29:35,035
Richard Portes, the most famous economist in Britain -

1391
01:29:35,203 --> 01:29:37,329
- and a professor at London Business School -

1392
01:29:37,497 --> 01:29:41,583
- was also commissioned by the lcelandic Chamber of Commerce -

1393
01:29:41,751 --> 01:29:45,796
- to write a report which praised the lcelandic financial sector.

1394
01:29:46,339 --> 01:29:48,215
The banks themselves are highly liquid.

1395
01:29:48,383 --> 01:29:51,176
They've made money on the fall of the Icelandic krona.

1396
01:29:51,344 --> 01:29:52,761
These are strong banks.

1397
01:29:52,929 --> 01:29:56,181
Their market funding is assured for the coming year.

1398
01:29:56,349 --> 01:29:58,308
-These are well-run banks. -Thank you.

1399
01:29:58,476 --> 01:30:01,812
Like Mishkin, Portes' report didn't disclose his payment -

1400
01:30:01,979 --> 01:30:04,481
- from the lcelandic Chamber of Commerce.

1401
01:30:04,649 --> 01:30:07,776
Does Harvard require disclosures of financial conflict of interest?

1402
01:30:10,988 --> 01:30:12,030
Not to my knowledge.

1403
01:30:12,198 --> 01:30:15,242
Do you require people to report the compensation -

1404
01:30:15,410 --> 01:30:17,953
- - received from outside activities? -No.

1405
01:30:18,121 --> 01:30:19,830
Don't you think that's a problem?

1406
01:30:19,997 --> 01:30:21,248
I don't see why.

1407
01:30:21,416 --> 01:30:24,084
Martin Feldstein being on the board of AIG -

1408
01:30:24,252 --> 01:30:26,169
- Laura Tyson at Morgan Stanley -

1409
01:30:26,337 --> 01:30:31,174
- Larry Summers making $1 0 million consulting to financial services firms - .

1410
01:30:31,342 --> 01:30:32,676
Irrelevant?

1411
01:30:32,844 --> 01:30:33,844
Yeah.

1412
01:30:34,011 --> 01:30:35,512
Yeah. Basically irrelevant.

1413
01:30:38,349 --> 01:30:41,184
You've written many articles about a wide array of subjects.

1414
01:30:41,352 --> 01:30:44,104
You never saw fit to investigate the risks -

1415
01:30:44,272 --> 01:30:47,607
- of unregulated credit default swaps?

1416
01:30:47,859 --> 01:30:49,526
I never did.

1417
01:30:49,694 --> 01:30:53,447
Same question with regard to executive compensation?

1418
01:30:53,614 --> 01:30:55,615
The regulation of corporate governance?

1419
01:30:55,783 --> 01:30:58,118
The effect of political contributions?

1420
01:30:58,286 --> 01:31:02,247
I don't know that l would have anything to add to those discussions.

1421
01:31:02,415 --> 01:31:04,499
I'm looking at your resume now.

1422
01:31:04,667 --> 01:31:09,463
It looks to me as if the majority of your outside activities -

1423
01:31:09,630 --> 01:31:12,466
- are consulting and directorship arrangements -

1424
01:31:12,633 --> 01:31:14,718
- with the financial services industry.

1425
01:31:14,886 --> 01:31:17,053
Would you not agree with that characterization?

1426
01:31:17,221 --> 01:31:20,515
To my knowledge, l don't think my consulting clients are on my CV.

1427
01:31:20,683 --> 01:31:23,560
-So I wouldn't know. -Who are your consulting clients?

1428
01:31:23,728 --> 01:31:25,896
I don't believe l have to discuss that with you.

1429
01:31:26,063 --> 01:31:27,230
Okay.

1430
01:31:27,857 --> 01:31:31,776
In fact, you have a few more minutes and the interview's over.

1431
01:31:31,944 --> 01:31:34,571
Do you consult for any financial services firms?

1432
01:31:34,739 --> 01:31:37,282
-The answer is l do. -And?

1433
01:31:37,450 --> 01:31:40,619
And-- But l do not wanna go into details about that.

1434
01:31:40,786 --> 01:31:43,580
Do they include other financial services firms?

1435
01:31:43,748 --> 01:31:44,915
Possibly.

1436
01:31:45,082 --> 01:31:46,750
You don't remember?

1437
01:31:46,918 --> 01:31:50,170
This isn't a deposition, sir. I was polite enough to give you time.

1438
01:31:50,338 --> 01:31:54,049
Foolishly, l now see. But you have three more minutes.

1439
01:31:54,217 --> 01:31:56,051
Give it your best shot.

1440
